<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06356179 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06356179 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; POLICE; MAN; INJURY; AID; ARREST; SUSPECT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A San Jose police officer who temporarily lost his memory after being shot inthe head when a Mount Hamilton drug raid soured nine months ago has recalledenough of his harrowing experience for sheriff's officers to arrest a Soledadstate prisoner on suspicion of attempted murder.;   Eliasar Angel Angulo wasarrested in his prison cell on the basis of a new interview with Officer JimWerkema, according to sheriff's Sgt. Ken Kahn.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  INJURED OFFICER REGAINS MEMORY, AIDS IN SOLEDADPRISONER'S ARREST  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Werkema, 33, could not be reached for comment Friday.;   But Kahn said hehas regained his memory and was interviewed again last week by Sgts. CaryColla and Earl Pennington.;   &quot;On the basis of his statements, the districtattorney issued a formal complaint of attempted murder against Angulo,&quot; Kahnsaid.;   Angulo is serving a one-year sentence on a parole violation for beingpresent at the rented mountain house of suspected methamphetamine dealerGregory Brookins during the pre-dawn drug raid March 19. Angulo was arrestedThursday.;   Werkema -- the first officer to burst into the Mount Hamiltonhome -- was met with a fusillade of bullets. He was shot in the jaw and ear bya bullet fired from the house, officers said. As he staggered backward, he washit again in the torso by another San Jose officer who was returning fire.;  The house burst into flames -- apparently from police tear gas grenades duringthe 45-minute shootout. When the fire died down, Brookins' badly burned bodywas found. He died of gunshot wounds and burns, although officials have neverdetermined whether bullets or the fire killed him.;   Brookins' 21-year-oldwife, Theresa, who was never charged in the case, and Angulo ran out of theburning house and surrendered. Angulo was arrested for parole violation andreturned to prison.;   Sheriff's detectives, who investigated the incidentbecause it happened in their jurisdiction, indicated at the time that Angulomight face more serious charges.;   Werkema, who was placed in a drug-inducedcoma when his brain swelled, could remember little of the events of the actualshooting shortly after his recovery, Kahn said. But he returned to duty a fewmonths ago and was interviewed a second time when he regained his memory, Kahnsaid.;   The sheriff's office now will seek a court order to get Anguloreleased from state prison and returned to Santa Clara County to be arraignedon the attempted murder charges.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  BETTY BARNACLE, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911221  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  398  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, December 21, 199100356179,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>